RABIES, FOX, HUMAN EXPOSURE - USA: (SOUTH CAROLINA, ARIZONA)
************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Sat 8 Nov 2008
Source: Goupstate.com [edited]
<http://www.goupstate.com/article/20081108/NEWS/811080319/1083/NEWS01?Title=Fox_that_attacked_worshippers_is_rabid>


The gray fox that attacked several members at an Inman church Wednesday [5
Nov 2008] was rabid, a health official said on Friday [7 Nov 2008].
Spartanburg County environmental enforcement director Don Arnold said tests
conducted on the fox by the SC [South Carolina] Department of Health and
Environmental Control [DHEC] came back positive for rabies.

The fox bit a 6 year old girl several times on the leg after first
attacking a 20 year old woman. The fox attacked the woman when she opened a
door at the church's family life center. The fox also bit another woman's
ankle several times and scratched at least 4 people at the Bishop Road
church. "This fox was so aggressive, so persistent, I've never seen
anything like it," David Duncan, the church pastor, told the Herald-Journal
on Thursday [6 Nov 2008]. "The fox couldn't be spooked."

The fox ran into the fellowship building and was chased out but ran into a
hallway of the main church building before it was again chased out. Church
members relied on folding chairs to defend themselves, and the fox had been
severely injured when animal control officers arrived at the scene.

Arnold said DHEC will notify the persons who were bitten or scratched about
vaccinations that will be required to prevent the disease from harming
them. DHEC spokesman Thom Berry said in a message that victims will be
administered 6 vaccinations over a 28-day period. Though the shots sound
grueling, the process is better than the alternative, a degenerative
progression that can be fatal. There is no cure for rabies.

Eight cases of rabies have been confirmed in animals in Spartanburg County
this year [2008]. Last year, South Carolina recorded 162 confirmed cases of
rabies in animals.

[byline: Craig Peters]

